title: Structuring SEO and Format of a page in Next.js Effectively

body.raw:
Organizing your Next.js application and using components. Imagine you want to use Next.js to build an application and that you want each page to have a distinct SEO strategy as well as the same header, footer, and navbar. What you can manage to do? The simple option is to build a shared component that is called repeatedly on each page. But, You might try this ðŸ‘‡ - I hope you have already developed a Next.js app before reading this. If not, visit this page ðŸ‘‰ [https://nextjs.org/docs/getting-started](https://nextjs.org/docs/getting-started) - Create two components with the names **Format** and SEOSetup in a new folder called **components** inside the src directory. This component, â€œFormat,â€ refers to the layout of the page. Here, in this case, the layout of every page will be in this flow **Navbar** then **Main** content, and then a **Footer**. And, We are therefore defining it below ðŸ‘‡ ```js import { FC } from 'react' import Footer from '../Footer' import Navbar from '../Navbar' const Format: FC = (props) => { return ( <>
{props.children}
) } export default Format ``` - In **SEOSetup**, weâ€™re really constructing a common tag with data supplied as props for the meta and title tag fields. So that we may utilize this **SEOSetup** component each time we need to define SEO-related information on a page rather than creating a head tag repeatedly. ```js import Head from 'next/head' export interface MetaData { title: string; description: string; } const SEOSetup: FC = (props) => { const { title, description } = props return ( {title} ) } export default SEOSetup ``` - Finally, utilize them on a page. Here we are just wrapping the page with the Format component and setting up SEO with our custom **SEOSetup** tag. ```js import type { NextPage } from 'next' import Format from '../components/Format' import SEOSetup from '../components/SEOSetup' const Home: NextPage = () => { return (
This is Home Page.
